Object_Definition: -- ============================================= -- Author:		Robert I. -- Create date: <2020-05-25 -- Description:	Need to query AD, lovingly stole this function from DW3. -- ============================================= CREATE FUNCTION [dbo].[fnSprintf] (@s varchar(MAX),                  @params varchar(MAX), @separator char(1) = ',') returns varchar(MAX) AS BEGIN declare @p varchar(MAX) declare @paramlen int  set @params = @params + @separator set @paramlen = len(@params) while not @params = '' begin     set @p = left(@params+@separator, charindex(@separator, @params)-1)     set @s = STUFF(@s, charindex('%s', @s), 2, @p)     set @params = substring(@params, len(@p)+2, @paramlen) end return @s END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @s varchar, @params varchar, @separator char)

Object_Definition: CREATE VIEW dbo.AD_Parents AS SELECT DISTINCT displayname, givenname, sn, mail, sAMAccountName, userPrincipalName, employeeType, CASE WHEN ADsPath LIKE '%Inactive_Parents%' THEN '0' ELSE '1' END AS ACTIVE FROM            (SELECT        displayname, givenname, sn, mail, sAMAccountName, userPrincipalName, ADsPath, employeeType                           FROM            OPENQUERY(ADSI,                                                      'SELECT 				employeeType 				, ADsPath 				, userPrincipalName 				, sAMAccountName 				, mail 				, sn 				, givenname 				, displayname   FROM  ''LDAP://entdc16.d204.ipsd.net/ou=Parents,ou=_1Support_and_System_Group,ou=_d204,dc=d204,DC=ipsd,DC=net''    WHERE objectCategory =  ''Person''   AND sn >= ''a*'' AND sn < ''ae*''   ')                                                      AS tblADSI                           UNION                           SELECT        displayname, givenname, sn, mail, sAMAccountName, userPrincipalName, ADsPath, employeeType                           FROM            OPENQUERY(ADSI,                                                     'SELECT 				employeeType 				, ADsPath 				, userPrincipalName 				, sAMAccountName 				, mail 				, sn 				, givenname 				, displayname   FROM Object_Definition: -- ============================================= -- Author:		Robert Iwataki -- Create date: 08/12/2020 -- Description:	Stored Procedure for fixing PushCoin User Issues. -- ============================================= CREATE PROCEDURE dbo.fix_users  	-- Add the parameters for the stored procedure here AS BEGIN 	-- SET NOCOUNT ON added to prevent extra result sets from 	-- interfering with SELECT statements. 	SET NOCOUNT ON;      -- Insert statements for procedure here UPDATE [PushCoin].[users].[UsersStaging] SET [LAST_NAME] = 'Rivera Jr' WHERE [STUDENT_ID] = '1052614' AND [STATE_STUDENT_ID] = '615226649';  DELETE FROM [PushCoin].[users].[UsersStaging] WHERE [STUDENT_ID] = '2016724' AND [ORGANIZATION_UNIT] = '28';  DELETE FROM [PushCoin].[users].[UsersStaging] WHERE [STUDENT_ID] = '2028091' AND [ORGANIZATION_UNIT] = '23';   END

Object_Definition: CREATE FUNCTION fnBirds (@StudentID uniqueidentifier) RETURNS VARCHAR(8000) AS BEGIN         DECLARE @Conf VARCHAR(8000)         SELECT @Conf = ''         SELECT @Conf = @Conf + [CONFERENCEINFO]         FROM [conCatTest2]         WHERE [STUDENT_GU] = @StudentID         AND [CONFERENCEINFO] IS NOT NULL         ORDER BY [SORTORDER] --yes we can sort   RETURN @Conf END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @StudentID uniqueidentifier)

Object_Definition: CREATE FUNCTION fnGetBooks (@AuthorID INT)   RETURNS VARCHAR(8000) AS BEGIN          DECLARE @BookList VARCHAR(8000)  SELECT @BookList =(           SELECT  BookName + ', ' AS [text()]        FROM    Books  WHERE AuthorID = @AuthorID         AND BookName IS NOT NULL      ORDER BY BookName        FOR XML PATH('') )           RETURN LEFT(@BookList,(LEN(@BookList) -1)) END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @AuthorID int)

Object_Definition: CREATE FUNCTION fnGetBooks2 (@AuthorID INT) RETURNS VARCHAR(8000) AS BEGIN         DECLARE @BookList VARCHAR(8000)         SELECT @BookList = ''         SELECT @BookList = @BookList + BookName +','         FROM Books         WHERE AuthorID = @AuthorID         AND BookName IS NOT NULL         ORDER BY BookName --yes we can sort   RETURN LEFT(@BookList,(LEN(@BookList) -1)) END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @AuthorID int)

Object_Definition: -- ============================================= -- Author:		Robert I. -- Create date: 06-22-20 -- Description:	Remove Special Characters. As used in eSchool. -- ============================================= CREATE FUNCTION [dbo].[RemoveSpecialChars] ( 	@s varchar(256) ) RETURNS varchar(256) AS BEGIN    if @s is null       return null 	set @s = (SELECT @s Collate SQL_Latin1_General_CP1253_CI_AI)    declare @s2 varchar(256)    set @s2 = ''    declare @l int    set @l = len(@s)    declare @p int    set @p = 1    while @p <= @l begin       declare @c int       set @c = ascii(substring(@s, @p, 1))        	  --letters only 	  if  @c between 65 and 90 or @c between 97 and 122          set @s2 = @s2 + char(@c)       set @p = @p + 1       end    if len(@s2) = 0       return null    return @s2 END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @s varchar)

Object_Definition: -- ============================================= -- Author:		Robert I. -- Create date: 06-22-2020 -- Description:	Stole this from eSchool. -- ============================================= CREATE FUNCTION [dbo].[TitleCase]  ( 	@InputString VARCHAR(4000) ) RETURNS VARCHAR(4000) AS BEGIN 	DECLARE @Index INT 	DECLARE @Char CHAR(1) 	DECLARE @OutputString VARCHAR(255) 	SET @OutputString = LOWER(@InputString)		--Start with everything in lower case 	SET @OutputString =	STUFF(@OutputString, 1, 1,UPPER(SUBSTRING(@InputString,1,1))) -- Overlay the first char of string with its upper case char 	SET @Index = 2	-- We already know that the first char is upper case, so get ready to look through the string at the 2nd position 	WHILE @Index <= LEN(@InputString) 		BEGIN 		SET @Char = SUBSTRING(@InputString, @Index, 1) --Get a char from the string 		IF @Char IN (' ', ';', ':', '!', '?', ',', '.', '_', '-', '/', '&','''','(') --Is the char a delimeter char? If so, the next letter should be capitalize 			IF @Index + 1 <= LEN(@InputString) 				BEGIN 					IF @Char != '''' OR UPPER(SUBSTRING(@InputString, @Index + 1, 1)) != 'S' 						SET @OutputString = 						STUFF(@OutputString, @Index + 1, 1,UPPER(SUBSTRING(@InputString, @Index + 1, 1))) 				END 			SET @Index = @Index + 1 	END 	RETURN ISNULL(@OutputString,'') END
Metadata: PARAMETERS: ( varchar OUT, @InputString varchar)

Object_Definition: -- ============================================= -- 07/19/2020 - Initial code -- ============================================= CREATE PROCEDURE dbo.SetSearchTime AS BEGIN 	-- SET NOCOUNT ON added to prevent extra result sets from 	-- interfering with SELECT statements. 	SET NOCOUNT ON;  TRUNCATE TABLE dbo.LastSearch;  INSERT INTO dbo.LastSearch (SearchTime) VALUES (GetDate());  END

Object_Definition: CREATE FUNCTION [dbo].[fnPTCConCat] (@StudentID uniqueidentifier) RETURNS VARCHAR(8000) AS BEGIN         DECLARE @Conf VARCHAR(8000)         SELECT @Conf = ''         SELECT @Conf = @Conf + [CONFERENCEINFO]         FROM [synergy].[ConferenceDisplay]         WHERE [STUDENT_GU] = @StudentID         AND [CONFERENCEINFO] IS NOT NULL         ORDER BY [SORTORDER] --yes we can sort   RETURN @Conf END
